commit.message: README.md: added examples of command usage

README.md: added detailed information on users file

Describes a bit more on what/how the users file is used with the init
command.

README.md: added information about git-grade

Added most of the necessary information about the tool. Need to add
setup.py and installation commands.

git-grade: added test command

As of now, `test` will traverse each repository and simply run the
commands pertinent to week 2's homework for my course. Of course this
can be made to accomodate a custom test, but I haven't the time to mess
with that right now.

git-grade: added deadline command

Deadline takes in a directory which holds initialized repositories, and
an optional timestamp in the form of YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS, military time.
Using this time, deadline will traverse the repos to see if the latest
commit was beyond the due date.

TODO: grade the most recent commit still
before a target time.

git-grade: added fetch command

Fetch will traverse all of the repositories within a specified directory
and simply fetch for new content. This is useful when students update
their work and one doesn't want to re-initialized a set of repos from
scratch.

git-grade: added verify command

Verify will take in a JSON file, which is a representation of a
desired folder structure to be tested against. Given a directory
containing these initialized git repositories, it will traverse each
repository and check to see if they have all of the required
folders/files specified by the JSON file.

The way the JSON file is formatted is fairly simple. If an item is a
directory, its key is another JSON. If an item is not a directory, its
key is null. For multiple files/folders in a given directory, they are
simply comma seperated within a JSON object, as a sort of list of things
within a directory.
git-grade: added help note for default init directory
git-grade: added default function to run

git-grade: added init command

init will take a list of line-seperated GitHub usernames, the name of
the common repository, and a directory to initialize each of these
repositories in. It then clones this common repository from each GitHub
account into folders named after each GitHub user within the directory
you specify.

Need to implement:
* verify: ensures each repository has the necessary files
* fetch: fetches the latest commits for each repository
* test: runs test scripts on each repository and generates a report
